1.body: Primordium is an experiment in emergent complexity . It transforms your host machine into a digital god where: CPU Workload becomes the environmental climate RAM Pressure controls resource scarcity Neural Networks emerge through natural selection Every legendary organism's DNA is preserved on blockchain Your machine becomes a god , and you become the observer Every run is unique. Every lineage is precious. Every extinction teaches us something.
1.title: What is Primordium?

31.body: Purpose: Ensure reproducible simulation with same seed Files: determinism.rs: Basic world determinism (100 ticks) determinism_suite.rs: Long-term determinism (200+ ticks with parallelism check)
31.title: 4. Determinism Tests

32.body: Purpose: Numerical stability, memory leaks, drift detection Files: stability_long_haul.rs: 2000 ticks, 500 entities (~30s) long_haul_suite.rs: Extended test suite (~2 hours) Quick check: 100 ticks Standard check: 1000 ticks Extended run: 5000 ticks with population dynamics Disaster resilience test Parallel determinism stress Boundary condition stress

33.body:
Every commit must pass: # 1. Code formatting
cargo fmt --all # 2. Linting (no warnings allowed)
cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings # 3. All tests
cargo test --workspace --all-features
33.title: Quality Gates

34.body: These quality gates are enforced via git hooks: pre-commit: Runs fmt, clippy, and tests pre-push: Runs full test suite
34.title: Pre-commit Hooks

36.body: Property-based testing complements example-based tests by: Discovering edge cases you wouldn't think of Testing thousands of inputs in a single test Capturing minimal counterexamples
36.title: Philosophy

37.body:
proptest! { #[test] fn test_brain_forward_no_nan( brain in arb_brain(50), inputs in any::<[f32; 29]>() ) { let (outputs, next_hidden) = brain.forward(inputs); for &o in &outputs { prop_assert!(o.is_finite()); } }
}

45.body: Long-haul tests are #[ignore] by default to keep CI fast. Run them: Before releases After major world/system changes When memory usage issues are suspected
45.title: CI Integration

47.body: Place unit tests in src/*/tests modules Place integration tests in tests/ Use #[tokio::test] for async tests Set config.world.deterministic = true for flaky tests Use existing builders from tests/common/ when possible
47.breadcrumbs: Testing Strategy Â» Adding New Tests
47.title: Adding New Tests

48.body: Run single test : cargo test --test brain_pbt test_brain_forward_no_nan Enable backtrace : RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo test --test failing_test Property test failure : Check .proptest-regressions/ for minimized counterexample Run with --nocapture to see debug output Determinism failure : Verify deterministic = true and seed is set Check for Uuid::new_v4() usage Ensure no system time dependencies
48.breadcrumbs: Testing Strategy Â» Debugging Failing Tests
48.title: Debugging Failing Tests

50.body: The perf_gate.rs test enforces tick time thresholds: 100 entities, 200 ticks, max 1500ms average tick time Scales with entity count Run with: cargo test --test perf_gate
50.title: Performance Gate

51.body:
# Release mode for performance tests
cargo test --release --test perf_gate # Measure memory usage
cargo test --release --test stability_long_haul -- --ignored
51.title: Benchmarking

52.body: Determinism First : Always test deterministic mode before random mode Property Tests : Add proptest for functions with complex input handling Descriptive Names : Use test_<feature>_<scenario> pattern Cleanup : Remove test logs and temporary files in setup()/teardown() Fast Feedback : Keep quick tests in CI, defer long-haul to manual runs Documentation : Add doc comments explaining test intent Last updated: 2026-02-26
52.title: Best Practices
